                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/1556: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 4, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>285. Your 493, October 4, 4 p.m. Please ascertain immediately if possible the
                    basis for the British opinion that a state of war does not exist. In particular,
                    is this attitude based upon legal considerations that relate to belligerent
                    rights, or is it only the result of practical considerations pending the Council
                    meeting. Any additional information along these lines will be much
                    appreciated.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
